he mill and eventually I became factory clerk - that was kind of an under foreman doing the clerical work there, and - as I told you this extra schooling I had with the - my teacher at - at the school, and I was a little bit more educated than what any of
 
the other boys was. Well they opened a new branch at Fulham - and the under foreman then was put in charge over there so the foreman at Price's in the sawmill wanted somebody to take his place, he tried about five - five of the boys there, or the young - 
y
oung - young men we were then - and they couldn't get on with it. He came up to me one - one day and he said, what sort of schooling did you have, Mr - or Harry he called me, what sort of schooling did you have? Oh, I said, oh pretty good, I went to night
 
school. He says, can you do decimal fractions? I said, oh yes. I forget every word about it. What's your handwriting like? I said, pretty good I think. Come up in the office, he said, and he gave ma a couple or three sums. Well - decimals I'd forgotten ev
e
ry word about, I really had - how to work them out. I said, well you'll have to refresh my memory Mr Gear, that was his - forman's name then - just show me one - one sum with decimals, one or two sums, he said - I said, and - if you can refresh my memory 
o
n decimals I said. He said what's your handwriting like? I said, oh pretty good. So I give him a sample of me handwriting. Oh yes, he said, well, he said, would you like to be my clerk up here? I said, very much sir. So that was raise up from working on t
