Oh I suppose about eighteen. Seventeen. Seventeen. Well - oh previous to that, I've got away from it now - previous to that one of the sawyers said, how much are you earning a week now? Well in the summertime whe
n it was - the weather was too hot or too warm for the candles to set we were put on short time. I was a packing case making - maker then. And - he said - you're not doing very good are you Harry? I said, no sir. Well we'd go in at quarter to nine in the 
m
orning and we were piecework there packing case making, we might have - two bobs worth of work of a morning, finish. So of course as they couldn't mould the candles there was - there was no necessity for making extra cases. So he said - I've got a friend,
 
he said, that's opening a - a new branch, he says, and they want a - a chap that can do packing - make packing cases and do a pack - a bit of packing, would you care about seeing him? I said, yes, I very much would. This is one of the sawyers at Price's. 
S
o - he took me round to see this - manager of this new place that was open and it was some three basement offices in Chancery lane, and the firm, well you may have heard of them, the Carborundum Company. Well - I got the job there. It was twenty-five bob 
a week, which was - which was a - a great - advantage of what I was earning at Price's you see, with this short time mind you. So I turned it up at Price's and I took this job on.
