se, about that time. And - I went to work for this Carborundum Company and I was doing very nicely there, it was only about nine o'clock in the morning 'til half past four in the afternoon and - perhaps go there and have nothing to do. It was a - a new br
a
nch they were opening out in England for the first time, they were a - they was American firm as you may know, and - he got a job there or the - the traveller had got a job - got an order rather - well these consignments of grinding wheels and so on - the
s
e abrasive materials from America I used to - oh big cases - I used to have to unpack those, put them in the - their different places, got a storeroom there and - knock these big cases down and cut the timber up to make cases perhaps for one grinding whee
l
. And - this traveller had got an order from - from a firm called Spear and Jackson's in Sheffield and he'd promised that they would have delivery of this - particular grinding wheel that they wanted on the first passenger train on Monday. Well - on the S
u
nday I - I met a friend of ours, he said, got a christening party - I used to play the piano a bit at those days - he said, we've got a christening party on Sunday Harry, he said, will you come round, play the piano for us? I said, yes. Had the christenin
g party you know, away I went there. Just started drinking beer at the time, and I got a hangover and I couldn't go to work on the Monday. 'Course when I did get to work this American }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12456976\charrsid15100875 boss}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9117970\charrsid15100875  he said, off - you're finished. And I got the sack from there. 'Cour
se I'd let the firm down you see, it was the first - one of the first orders this Carborundum Company had got in Sheffield - Spear and Jackson's, of course you know that firm, and of course I'd disappointed them, they hadn't got their wheel. So I got the 
s
ack from there. Didn't know what to do, where to go and find a job, I - oh before I left Price's I give 'em notice you know and left in the proper manner, he says, any time you want a job, come and see me, he said, you can always have your job back again.
 
I was getting on very nicely at Price's. So - I hadn't got the face to go back - I think - it'd only be the same again, short time in the summer when it was hot, no I don't want to go back there again, so I didn't trouble. Well - various places I tried to
 
get a job, used to go out nicely dressed you know, bowler hat, collar and tie, nice - nice clothes, you know, shined boots and - walking round, and they were just building the - Central Criminal Courts at the Old Bailey. Saw a notice - 'course used to go 
o
ut walking - don't know where I walked to - walked - oh - Shireditch and back again, you couldn't ride you see, I'd got no money. So - I saw this place as I was passing down the Old Bailey there, mason's labourers wanted. Didn't know a thing about masons 
l
abouring. Well went there, 'course different people I'd met, they'd told me how to go about these building jobs. I'd got a bowler hat on, it's in February this was, snowing - well I don't now what the masons labourers job is, I went to find the clerk of t
he works, I was told where to find him, what's a masons labourer, do you know anything about it? Oh yes. Oh yes. You had a bit of - bit of kid wallop onto 'em then. Well, he said, go and see {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Mr Lane{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} he said, you'll find him somewhere, he's up the top there.
 Bowler hat, overcoat, collar and tie, shined boots. I had to climb up ladders, go along gantries, up - up other ladders, right at the top underneath the status of justice. That's where I find him. The job was - they'd finished the building you see, it wa
s cleaning down the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 stonework for which we had to get a worn out paint brush, a three inch paint brush you know, a pail of water and a bath brick. Splash the water on this stonework and rub down with this - well that was all - sevenpence an hour, t
wenty-nine and tuppence a week for fifty hours. Oh I was on velvet there.
